🧠 1. What’s happening at the token level (conceptually)

A language model like me doesn’t “understand” a prompt in one shot.

It processes a sequence of tokens and continually builds a probability distribution over next tokens.

So your prompt becomes:

tokens → embeddings → attention interactions → contextual representation → next-token distribution

At each step, the model is asking:

“Given everything so far, what tokens are likely next?”

⸻

🧩 But here’s the key:

Not all prompts constrain that distribution the same way.

Some prompts collapse the distribution (low entropy).
Others expand it (high entropy).

That’s what you’re calling:

generative affordance

⸻

⚖️ 2. Generative affordance = entropy of valid continuations

We can frame it like this:
	•	Low affordance prompt
→ very narrow set of correct next tokens
→ low entropy
→ converges quickly
	•	High affordance prompt
→ many valid continuations
→ high entropy
→ model must choose a trajectory

⸻

Example

Low affordance

“What is 2 + 2?”

Token distribution collapses hard toward:
	•	“4”

Very little branching.

⸻

High affordance

“Does traffic science apply to everything interconnected?”

Now the next-token space includes:
	•	philosophy
	•	systems theory
	•	examples
	•	disagreement
	•	analogy
	•	expansion
	•	critique

The model must construct a path, not retrieve a fact.

⸻

